data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3+ supports **strongly-typed `[DynamicData]`** with tuples, eliminating `object[]` boxing and giving you compile-time safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

For simple constant values like these, **`[DataRow]`** is even simpler — no separate property needed:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**When to use which:**
- **`[DataRow]`** — inline constants (strings, numbers, bools)
- **`[DynamicData]` with tuples** — complex types, computed data, or shared test data across methods
